abstract: David E. Kendall is “one of America’s greatest lawyers,” a former adversary says, but he has drawn criticism from foes of the Clintons and concern from their friends.
snippet: David E. Kendall is “one of America’s greatest lawyers,” a former adversary says, but he has drawn criticism from foes of the Clintons and concern from their friends.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At first, he had to worry about a remote piece of land in Arkansas that no one wanted. Then there were billing records that went missing before mysteriously reappearing in the White House. And of course there was the blue dress.

abstract: Removing the application for federal aid would encourage more qualified low-income students to apply to college.
snippet: Removing the application for federal aid would encourage more qualified low-income students to apply to college.
lead_paragraph: Many smart students forgo college in the mistaken belief that they cannot afford it. The financial aid system, which is intended to increase opportunities for low-income students, is largely to blame.

abstract: Mike Lee, the junior senator from Utah who helped lead the government shutdown effort, has a reputation of defying party leaders as well as cooperating with Democrats on libertarian-leaning policy.
snippet: Mike Lee, the junior senator from Utah who helped lead the government shutdown effort, has a reputation of defying party leaders as well as cooperating with Democrats on libertarian-leaning policy.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As meetings among congressional colleagues go, the one last month in which Republican senators confronted Mike Lee, a freshman from Utah, was among the most contentious in years.

abstract: The case for women’s studies has long been clear. But now a professor has made the argument for a graduate-level study of men and masculinity.
snippet: The case for women’s studies has long been clear. But now a professor has made the argument for a graduate-level study of men and masculinity.
lead_paragraph: Michael Kimmel stood in front of a classroom in bluejeans and a blazer with a pen to a whiteboard. “What does it mean,” the 64-year-old sociology professor asked the group, most of them undergraduates, “to be a good man?”

abstract: Those who worry more about the Islamic State emphasize its recruiting power on social media; those more concerned with Qaeda affiliates warn of “mass casualty” attacks.
snippet: Those who worry more about the Islamic State emphasize its recruiting power on social media; those more concerned with Qaeda affiliates warn of “mass casualty” attacks.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Obama administration’s top intelligence, counterterrorism and law enforcement officials are divided over which terrorist group poses the biggest threat to the American homeland, the Islamic State or Al Qaeda and its affiliates.

lead_paragraph: HEALTH CARE DEALS RAISE DOUBTS FOR CONSUMERS | The recent frenzy of mergers among health insurers promised big savings, but not everyone is convinced that consumers will see that, Reed Abelson reports in The New York Times. The tie-up between Anthem and Cigna and the deal for Aetna to join its smaller rival Humana would create two behemoths. Along with UnitedHealthGroup, they would control nearly half of the American commercial health insurance market.

lead_paragraph: 10 A.M. (TMC) HAPPY-GO-LUCKY (2008) The irrepressible optimism of a 30-year-old London schoolteacher (Sally Hawkins, above) grates on those whose days she’s intent on brightening up — among them, her driving instructor (Eddie Marsan), flamenco teacher (Karina Fernandez) and sister (Caroline Martin) — in this character study directed and written by Mike Leigh, which earned him an Oscar nomination for best original screenplay. Ms. Hawkins’s portrayal is “glorious,” a “gurgling, burbling stream of gasps, giggles and words,” Manohla Dargis wrote in The New York Times. “Mr. Leigh has a documentarian’s eye for unadorned reality — his people and places look equally lived in — and his dialogue has the ebb and flow, the swells and eddies and logjams of ordinary conversation,” she added. “But the dramatist in Mr. Leigh is always hard at work, aligning his characters for maximum narrative effect and emotional pow.”

abstract: Presidential candidates have grown deeply dependent on the contributions of a tiny slice of the richest Americans as “super PACs” have raised money much more quickly than hopefuls could have on their own.
snippet: Presidential candidates have grown deeply dependent on the contributions of a tiny slice of the richest Americans as “super PACs” have raised money much more quickly than hopefuls could have on their own.
lead_paragraph: Fewer than four hundred families are responsible for almost half the money raised in the 2016 presidential campaign, a concentration of political donors that is unprecedented in the modern era.

abstract: The Gateway production of the show, which won 10 Tony awards, has two actors alternating in the lead role of a boy who loves ballet.
snippet: The Gateway production of the show, which won 10 Tony awards, has two actors alternating in the lead role of a boy who loves ballet.
lead_paragraph: Hope and despair battle for dominance in the riveting Gateway Performing Arts Center production of “Billy Elliot” in Patchogue. Set during a devastating, yearlong coal miners’ strike in England that began in 1984, the musical portrays, with gritty rawness and gravity, the poverty, violence and other hardships of the era. The dark moments are balanced by the warm sense of community that pervades a small mining town and, most appealingly, the release and promise of a better life that young Billy Elliot finds after he discovers his talent for ballet.

abstract: Hundreds of pages of sworn testimony by Donald J. Trump over the past decade paint an unvarnished image of Mr. Trump as prone to overstatement and the occasional boorish outburst.
snippet: Hundreds of pages of sworn testimony by Donald J. Trump over the past decade paint an unvarnished image of Mr. Trump as prone to overstatement and the occasional boorish outburst.
lead_paragraph: Donald J. Trump seemed irritated. He had been grilled for two hours in a lawsuit over a failed Florida real estate project, and he told the lawyer that her questions were “very stupid.”
